╭────────────────────────────── Incident Report ───────────────────────────────╮
│ ## Executive Summary                                                         │
│                                                                              │
│ The investigation revealed a confirmed APT compromise on the Windows 10 x64  │
│ system. The threat actor deployed multiple malware components including a    │
│ suspicious process named "license_ctrl.e" operating as a local listener      │
│ service on port 5682, and "ftusbsrvc.exe" masquerading as a USB service      │
│ while listening on port 33001. Network analysis confirmed command and        │
│ control (C2) communications to external infrastructure at 172.16.4.10:8080,  │
│ indicating active threat actor presence and data exfiltration capabilities.  │
│                                                                              │
│ ## Timeline of Events                                                        │
│                                                                              │
│ Based on process creation timestamps and network activity:                   │
│ - 2018-09-05 14:27:55: ftusbsrvc.exe established listening service on port   │
│ 33001                                                                        │
│ - 2018-09-06 17:17:20: license_ctrl.e process initiated listening on port    │
│ 5682                                                                         │
│ - Multiple timeframes: Active C2 communications to 172.16.4.10:8080 with     │
│ connection states showing CLOSED/CLOSE_WAIT indicating completed data        │
│ exchanges                                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ ## Indicators of Compromise                                                  │
│                                                                              │
│ **Malicious Processes:**                                                     │
│ - license_ctrl.e (PID 1716) - Suspicious executable with non-standard        │
│ extension                                                                    │
│ - ftusbsrvc.exe (PID 4916) - Masquerading as legitimate USB service          │
│                                                                              │
│ **Network Indicators:**                                                      │
│ - 172.16.4.10:8080 - External C2 infrastructure                              │
│ - Local ports 5682 and 33001 - Unusual listening services                    │
│                                                                              │
│ **Behavioral Indicators:**                                                   │
│ - Multiple closed TCP connections indicating completed C2 sessions           │
│ - Processes listening on non-standard ports                                  │
│ - Suspicious process naming conventions                                      │
│                                                                              │
│ ## Persistence Mechanisms                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ The threat actor established persistence through:                            │
│ - ftusbsrvc.exe service masquerading as legitimate USB functionality         │
│ - license_ctrl.e local listener providing backdoor access                    │
│ - Both processes configured to listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0)            │
│                                                                              │
│ ## Recommendations                                                           │
│                                                                              │
│ **Immediate Actions:**                                                       │
│ 1. Isolate the affected system from the network                              │
│ 2. Block communications to 172.16.4.10 at the perimeter                      │
│ 3. Hunt for similar IOCs across the enterprise                               │
│ 4. Preserve memory and disk images for further analysis                      │
│                                                                              │
│ **Remediation:**                                                             │
│ 1. Remove identified malicious processes                                     │
│ 2. Conduct full system rebuild from known-good state                         │
│ 3. Reset all user credentials that may have been compromised                 │
│ 4. Implement enhanced monitoring for the identified TTPs                     │
│                                                                              │
│ **Long-term Improvements:**                                                  │
│ 1. Deploy endpoint detection and response (EDR) solutions                    │
│ 2. Implement network segmentation                                            │
│ 3. Enhance threat hunting capabilities                                       │
│ 4. Conduct purple team exercises focusing on identified techniques           │
│                                                                              │
│ ## Evidence References                                                       │
│                                                                              │
│ - Volatility process list analysis showing suspicious executables            │
│ - Network connection analysis revealing C2 communications                    │
│ - Process-to-network mapping confirming malicious activity                   │
│ - Timestamp correlation establishing attack timeline                         │
